Ben Shelton may not have hoped for the start he's had at the Nitto ATP Finals, but his perspective remains as sharp as his serve.

After a narrow three-set defeat to Felix Auger-Aliassime on Wednesday, the 23-year-old American slipped to 0-2 on his debut appearance at the season finale in Turin. Yet even in disappointment, Shelton's optimism and competitiveness shone through.

In a gripping contest defined by bold play and razor-thin margins, Shelton's fearless shotmaking was momentarily tested at 2/4 in the second-set tie-break, when he took a tumble and was left grimacing and limping between points for the remainder of the set.

“I think it should be okay. It was just one of those where it hit really hard on the ground,” Shelton said of his left knee. “It hurt really bad for the next 10, 15 minutes. I wasn't about to stop and call the trainer, then come back and try to serve down a mini-break and stay in the set. I just kept going, maybe [due to] adrenaline. But I didn't feel it at all through the whole third set.”

The fall came at a crucial moment, but Shelton's desire to carry on epitomised his fighting spirit, one that has become a defining trait throughout his 2025 campaign.

